h `stateIdle` for every selected provider only.\n\n```go\nfunc TestStartRunBuildsOrderAndState(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.program = fakeProgram() // required — startRun's goroutines call m.program.Send\n\tm.selected[2] = true\n\tm.selected[0] = true\n\tm.startRun()\n\n\t// order should follow `providers` slice order, not selection order\n\twant := []string{providers[0], providers[2]}\n\tif !reflect.DeepEqual(m.runOrder, want) {\n\t\tt.Errorf(\"runOrder = %v, want %v\", m.runOrder, want)\n\t}\n\tif m.pending != 2 {\n\t\tt.Errorf(\"pending = %d, want 2\", m.pending)\n\t}\n\tfor _, name := range want {\n\t\tif m.statuses[name] == nil || m.statuses[name].state != stateIdle {\n\t\t\tt.Errorf(\"expected %s seeded idle\", name)\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\tm.waitForGoroutines() // test-only hook, or inject a fake runCrawler\n}\n```\n\n**Structural gap**: `startRun` currently calls the package-level `runCrawler` directly and spawns real goroutines that shell out to `uv run main.py`. To unit-test `startRun`'s state-management logic without launching real subprocesses, `runCrawler` needs to be injectable (e.g. a `crawlerFn func(name string, limit int, dir string, onLine func(string)) error` field on `model`, defaulted to the real `runCrawler` in `newModel` and swapped for a fake in tests). Same applies to `runHeadless` in main.go.\n\n### 5. `runCrawler` / `runHeadless` — no unit or integration coverage at all\n\nThese are the two functions with real external side effects (subprocess exec) and currently **cannot be unit tested** without either refactoring or a filesystem fixture, since `exec.Command(\"uv\", \"run\", \"main.py\", ...)` is hardcoded.\n\n```go\n// main_test.go\n\n// TestRunCrawlerStreamsStdout uses a fake crawlerDir containing a minimal\n// script standing in for `uv run main.py`, to prove line-by-line streaming\n// and stdout/stderr folding without depending on the real Python crawler.\nfunc TestRunCrawlerStreamsStdoutLineByLine(t *testing.T) {\n\t// Requires either:\n\t//  (a) refactoring runCrawler to accept an exec.Cmd factory (preferred —\n\t//      makes this fully unit-testable with a stub), or\n\t//  (b) writing a temp dir with a fake `main.py` (or swapping `uv` for a\n\t//      test binary via PATH manipulation) as a real subprocess integration test.\n\tt.Skip(\"gap: runCrawler has no seam for injecting a fake subprocess\")\n}\n\nfunc TestRunCrawlerPropagatesNonZeroExit(t *testing.T) {\n\t// Gap: cmd.Wait() error path (non-zero exit code) is never asserted.\n\tt.Skip(\"gap: needs subprocess seam, see above\")\n}\n\nfunc TestRunCrawlerFoldsStderrIntoSameStream(t *testing.T) {\n\t// Gap: cmd.Stderr = cmd.Stdout behavior (scrapling logs on stderr) is\n\t// asserted only by comment, never by test.\n\tt.Skip(\"gap: needs subprocess seam, see above\")\n}\n\nfunc TestRunHeadlessAggregatesAcrossProviders(t *testing.T) {\n\t// Gap: concurrent fan-out via sync.WaitGroup, per-provider \"[name] line\"\n\t// / \"[name] error: ...\" print format — no coverage. Needs runCrawler\n\t// injected as a func field/param to avoid real subprocess calls.\n\tt.Skip(\"gap: runHeadless calls package-level runCrawler directly, not injectable\")\n}\n```\n\n### 6. `main()` — flag parsing and dispatch branch, untested\n\n```go\nfunc TestMainFlagDefaults(t *testing.T) {\n\t// Gap: no test proves --limit defaults to 10, --crawler-dir defaults to\n\t// \"../crawler\", --providers defaults to \"all\", or that --headless\n\t// correctly short-circuits to runHeadless vs. launching the TUI.\n\t// main() as written is not decomposed for testing — recommend extracting\n\t// flag-parsing + dispatch into a `run(args []string) error` function that\n\t// main() calls with os.Args[1:], enabling this test without a real process spawn.\n\tt.Skip(\"gap: main() not decomposed into a testable run(args) function\")\n}\n```\n\n### 7. Missing integration-level test: full TUI flow end-to-end\n\nNo test drives the model through picking → limit → running via real `Update()` calls, which is where regressions in the state machine would actually surface (e.g. viewport sizing before first `WindowSizeMsg`, sidenav highlight tracking during a run).\n\n```go\n// Consider adding github.com/charmbracelet/x/exp/teatest (not currently a\n// dependency) for a scripted end-to-end run:\nfunc TestFullFlowPickLimitRun(t *testing.T) {\n\t// 1. send WindowSizeMsg\n\t// 2. press space on provider 0, enter -> screenLimit\n\t// 3. type \"1\", enter -> screenRunning, assert runOrder/pending\n\t// 4. send statusMsg + doneMsg for the provider, assert sidenav shows done\n\t// 5. assert 'q' now quits (pending==0)\n\tt.Skip(\"gap: no end-to-end model-driven test exists\")\n}\n```\n\n### 8. View-rendering functions — untested, lower priority\n\n`viewPicking`, `viewLimit`, `viewRunning`, `View()` produce ANSI/lipgloss-styled strings. Full snapshot testing is low value given styling churn, but a **smoke test** (non-empty output, no panic, contains expected literal substrings like provider names or `\"0 of 11 selected\"`) would catch outright breakage cheaply:\n\n```go\nfunc TestViewsDoNotPanicAndContainKeyText(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.width, m.height = 120, 40\n\tif out := m.viewPicking(); !strings.Contains(out, \"IKOTOFETSY\") {\n\t\tt.Error(\"viewPicking missing expected badge text\")\n\t}\n\tm.screen = screenLimit\n\tif out := m.viewLimit(); !strings.Contains(out, \"how many new articles\") {\n\t\tt.Error(\"viewLimit missing expected prompt\")\n\t}\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Summary of gaps by priority\n\n1. **No tests exist at all** — establish `tui_test.go` / `main_test.go` with the pure-function suite in §1 first; zero refactoring required, immediate coverage.\n2. **`handleKey`/`Update` state machine (§2–3)** — the highest-value target; catches real regressions in the interactive flow. No refactor needed.\n3. **Nil-pointer gap on unknown-provider messages (§3)** — worth a guard + regression test even though currently unreachable.\n4. **`truncate` negative-n panic and multi-byte-UTF8 mis-slice (§1)** — latent bugs, currently unreachable via existing call sites, but should be pinned by a test if `truncate` is ever called with dynamic input.\n5. **Subprocess boundary (`runCrawler`, `runHeadless`, `startRun`) is completely untestable as written** — needs a small refactor (inject a `crawlerFn`) before any unit test can cover process-exec error handling, non-zero exit propagation, or stdout/stderr folding. This is the biggest structural gap.\n6. **`main()` dispatch logic** — needs extraction into a testable `run(args []string)` before it's coverable.\n",
